<HL>
   After the Show, the Newscasters
   Climb In With Buckets and Shovels
   ----
   By Craig Forman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Forces in the Persian Gulf may be armed with
state-of-the-art equipment, but British television is relying
on turn-of-the-century visual aids.
   Since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, the British Broadcasting
Corp.'s flagship "Newsnight" program has used a studio model
about the size of a pingpong table to illustrate the naval
and troop buildup in the Persian Gulf. In nightly maneuvers
reflecting the day's military developments, tiny green tanks
deploy menacingly along the Iraqi-Saudi border. Miniature
U.S. jet fighters swoop over sand-colored polystyrene hills.
And the Persian Gulf becomes increasingly crowded with metal
warships marked with flags, like bite-sized sausages at a
July 4th picnic.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The tone of the program -- usually a sophisticated hybrid
of ABC's "Nightline" and the U.S. networks' nightly news --
changes when avuncular BBC anchorman Peter Snow runs to his
table-top sandbox. There, he plays out tactics with a platoon
of retired British admirals and generals.
   To some people, this seems unseemly. "It struck me as
children playing with their toys -- like an elaborate train
set," says John Lyttle, television critic at Britain's
Independent newspaper.
   The BBC defends the #1,200 ($2,350) model as an efficient
way to illustrate the fast-changing Gulf situation. "It may
be seen to be unsophisticated," says Tim Gardam, editor of
"Newsnight." "But it has greater flexibility and greater
clarity than two-dimensional computer graphics." In
particular, he says it shows three-dimensional terrain --
useful for strategic commentary -- better than the "quick
graphic movements, little blobs and clipped interviews" that
he sees on U.S. networks.
   The program's producers may be just getting back into
practice; the BBC used similar models to illustrate the
Falklands War and the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan. But
they display a gift for ingenuity. When news broke late that
hostages in Kuwait would be moved to city hotels, the BBC
improvised with what looked like matchboxes placed on end.
When Yemen decided an hour before airtime that it wouldn't
unload an Iraqi tanker, one metal ship found itself adrift in
the Gulf.
   But this model's days may be numbered. Mr. Gardam says the
program, which has a modeler, three producers and an
assistant manipulating the sandbox, is working on a bigger
and better version.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900827-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900827-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   East German Future
   Isn't Hopeless, Official
   At Bundesbank Says
</HL>
<DATE>
08/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3A
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKFURT -- The financial state and future prospects for
East German industry are not "hopeless," Claus Koehler, a
director of the Bundesbank said on West German radio.
   Mr. Koehler, who is the central bank's directorate member
responsible for credit markets, apparently is optimistic. "We
mustn't go on the assumption that we are in a hopeless
situation" regarding the health and outlook for East German
industry, the official said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He said the central bank polled 140 enterprises with more
than 200,000 employees in East Germany over their
expectations, and said the Bundesbank was "astonished" with
the favorable nature of the replies.
   Mr. Koehler said one-third of the respondents expect to
boost production, while another third foresee output trends
at current levels. Only one-third anticipate falling
production, Mr. Koehler said.
   He added that the companies noted that the East German
economy is "fully ailing," but asserted that their prospects
aren't bad. "We know that we have to pass through a deep
valley that will be especially characterized by high
unemployment. But expectations are improving," Mr. Koehler
said.
   Mr. Koehler also said that after Oct. 3, when the two
Germanys expect to merge, it would make sense for West
Germany to undertake an emergency financial cash infusion to
support the economically strapped area that is now East
Germany.
   He said the West German government shouldn't raise taxes
to finance the cost of integrating and overhauling East
Germany, but should be willing to broaden its budget deficit
if necessary.
</TEXT>
