</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   JR WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   RICHMOND, Va. -- James River Corp. said four executives
were given broader responsibilities as part of an effort to
simplify the paper-products company's business structure and
boost its resources for expansion.
   Charles E. Eberle, who had directed the company's U.S.
towel and tissue operations, was named executive vice
president in charge of all consumer-product businesses. The
new grouping accounts for about 50% of James River's domestic
sales.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Norman K. Ryan, who had headed paperboard operations, was
named executive vice president for packaging. Combined
operations for food and consumer packaging contribute about
30% of total company sales.
   Ernest S. Leopold, a former senior vice president and
group executive, was picked as executive vice president of
communications papers, the company's coated printing-papers
business.
   Ronald B. Estridge, the company's technology executive in
charge of research and development, assumed additional duties
for directing fiber and energy operations.
