<HL>
   Short Interest
   Drops in OTC's
   Two Categories
   ---
   TW Holdings Inc. Figure
   Shows Largest Increase
   In Month to Mid-August
   ----
   By Robert J. Brennan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
SHORT SALES AND SHORT INTEREST (SHO)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Short interest among over-the-counter stocks,
both large and small, edged down in the month ended in
mid-August after small issues leaped the prior month and
larger issues edged up.
   TW Holdings Inc., Spartanburg, S.C., which owns and
operates restaurants, principally 470 Hardee's fast-food
outlets, led the issues with the largest increase in short
interest. Short position in the company rose more than one
million shares, to nearly 2.2 million. Last month it reported
second-quarter and six-month losses of $12.7 million and
$58.8 million, respectively, against net income of $20.8
million and $29.6 million. The losses were attributed to debt
and other expenses in the 1989 acquisition of TW Services
Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Acclaim Entertainment Inc., a major licensee of Nintendo
computer games based in Oyster Bay, N.Y., saw short interest
in its shares soar to 785,281 from 225,643 a month earlier.
Acclaim recently lifted restrictions on a block of its stock
held by entertainment giant MCA Inc., clearing MCA to sell
it. Also, it plans to make a new offering of two million
shares; current shares outstanding total 18.7 million.
   Puget Sound Bancorp, Tacoma, Wash., had practically no
short position in the prior month, but in the recent period
short interest shot up to 544,633 shares. It was one of
several bank and thrift issues that were among the leaders in
short interest. Puget Sound, however, recently reported good
quarterly results and last month increased its dividend,
raising the possibility that investors were seeking to
capture the dividend.
   First Executive Corp., a Los Angeles life insurance
company that once held a large portfolio of junk bonds, again
was the volume leader in short interest, with nearly 8.5
million shares, up from 8.3 million at mid-July.
   Among the companies with the largest decreases in short
interest, Intel Corp. dropped 80%, to 588,393 shares from the
previous month's 4.3 million. The chip maker in July reported
substantial increases in profit and revenue for the second
quarter and six months.
   Furon Co., a Laguna Niguel, Calif.-based maker of
polymers, had short interest practically disappear, to 6,700
shares from more than 900,000. The company in June announced
a plan to redeem a debenture issue for either cash or stock.
   Traders who sell short borrow stock and sell it, betting
that the stock's price will decline and that they can buy the
shares back later at a lower price for return to the lender.
   Short interest is the number of shares that haven't yet
been purchased for return to lenders. Although a substantial
short position reflects heavy speculation that a stock's
price will decline, some investors consider an increase in
short interest bullish because the borrowed shares eventually
must be bought back.
   And some short interest doesn't reflect any opinion on the
stock at all but shows up as part of another strategy, such
as arbitrage or dividend capture.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, the
self-regulatory agency that operates the Nasdaq computerized
system on which more than 4,300 OTC issues trade, compiles
short interest data in two categories: the approximately
two-thirds, and generally biggest, Nasdaq stocks that trade
on the National Market System; and the other, generally
smaller stocks that don't.
   NASD reported that short interest in 2,335 National Market
System issues, the largest OTC stocks, totaled 255.5 million
shares at mid-August, down from a revised 256.9 million in
mid-July among 2,299 issues.
   Short interest in 1,232 smaller securities traded on
Nasdaq declined to 37.7 million shares in August from a
revised 38.5 million in July among 1,212 issues.
   The National Market System's short-interest ratio at
mid-August fell to 2.19 from a revised 2.58 a month earlier,
while the short-interest ratio for other OTC issues climbed
to 1.06 from a revised 0.96.
   The ratio -- the number of trading days at the market's
average daily trading volume that would be required to
convert the total short interest position -- is a measure of
negative trader sentiment. Some analysts suggest, however,
that the ratio has weakened in value as an indicator because
options and other products can be used to hedge short
positions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900827-0029
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900827-0029.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Enterprise:
   After Slowdown, New Strategies for Venture Capitalists
   ----
   By Udayan Gupta
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<LP>
   "For venture capitalists, it'll never again be business as
usual. The industry is paying the price of success."
   So says William Sahlman, a professor of entrepreneurial
finance at the Harvard Business School.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   After successfully financing some of America's best-known
high-growth companies, including Federal Express Corp., Apple
Computer Inc. and Compaq Computer Corp., the venture-capital
industry began to hit rough times. The industry's average
annual return on investment, which ran as high as 30% a
decade ago, has been falling sharply for the past five years.
Many venture funds have had trouble raising capital.
   Venture-capital partnerships, which provide financing for
young companies, attracted a wave of new capital after their
phenomenal success in the 1970s and early 1980s. But the
increase in capital bid up the prices venture capitalists
paid for investments and cut returns, Mr. Sahlman says. "Too
many companies were being funded in the same industries, and
the inevitable result was competitive mayhem."
   The 39-year-old Mr. Sahlman has been studying
entrepreneurship and venture capital for over a decade. His
Harvard Business School course on entrepreneurial finance
attracts over 50% of the school's second-year class. He is
also a director of two Boston companies, Avid Technology
Inc., a provider of video editing software, and Butcher Co.,
a 110-year old manufacturer of industrial sanitary supply
goods.
   "The rates of return for the foreseeable future will not
reach the levels" of the late '70s and early '80s, he
predicts. But the problems of the past five years seem to be
clearing the way for new opportunities and new strategies. In
an interview, Mr. Sahlman considered the future of venture
capital and entrepreneurship in America:
                                                                                                       

   Q. Is venture capital dead?
   A. Not by a long shot. The prospects for the industry in
the 1990s are better than they have been for over a decade.
   Less capital and fewer funds means fewer companies will be
financed. The companies that do receive money will get more
attention from their investors and have a better chance of
survival. The rates of return will increase from the low
levels experienced in the past five or six years.
                                                                                                       

   Q. Will we see a change in the way venture capitalists
invest?
   A. Yes. Venture capitalists are going to look for fewer
home runs -- companies that potentially can achieve sales of
$500 million or so. They are going to invest in smaller
companies that can dominate a niche, companies that often may
be no bigger than $50 million to $100 million in sales, but
highly profitable.
                                                                                                       

   Q. What else will have to change?
   A. Venture capitalists will have to open up their
investment horizons. That means going beyond traditional
high-tech ideas such as workstations and semiconductors. It
might make more sense to look at service businesses that
could improve with the application of technology. More
important, they will have to cast the entrepreneurial net
wider to include women, as well as minorities.
                                                                                                       

   Q. What role will venture capitalists have to play in this
new environment?
   A. They have to provide more than just money. They will
need to develop closer ties with the companies they invest
in, provide more help with recruiting and strategic
partnering. They also will have to help their companies with
competitive positioning in a new and ever-changing global
marketplace.
   Venture capitalists have to recognize that they aren't the
only sources of capital for fast-growing companies. They face
competition from other venture capitalists, from angels, from
corporate investors and from institutions investing directly
in start-up businesses.
                                                                                                       

   Q. What are the implications for entrepreneurs?
   A. There are plenty of sources of risk capital for
entrepreneurs today. They need to choose their sources of
capital carefully for the best chances of success.
   Searching for the cheapest capital may not be in the best
long-term interest of a growing company. From whom you raise
money often is more important than the terms on which you
obtain that money.
   Going public may seem like a good way to get cheap money,
but it also can cause long-term business strategies to be
jettisoned. Many managers hurt their companies in order to
try to live up to the unrealistic expectations embedded in
high public market stock prices.
                                                                                                       

   Q. What are the alternatives to venture capital?
   A. Angels, for one. The entrepreneurial revolution created
many successes, such as H. Ross Perot, who themselves are
investing in new ventures. Institutional investors -- Harvard
University's endowment, for example -- that only invested
through venture-capital partnerships are investing directly.
   And then there are the corporations, both domestic and
international, that are moving up the food chain, investing
earlier in the development of new companies. For many small
companies, finding a corporate partner that can help in their
overall growth may be more helpful than trying to cash out
quickly by going public.
                                                                                                       

   Q. Should government try to provide capital for
entrepreneurial businesses?
   A. No. Government efforts to encourage entrepreneurship
would be more effective if focused on helping companies sell
products and services than if focused on access to financing.
Loan guarantees often result in poor investment decisions and
shift risk to taxpayers without sufficient macroeconomic
benefits. Such efforts might make more sense if there was a
genuine shortage of risk capital, but I don't believe a
shortage exists.
                                                                                                       

   Q. Should the government play any role in helping the
entrepreneurial climate?
   A. Government should stop changing policies that have an
impact on risk-taking and entrepreneurship. It also can
simplify and reduce the cost of raising capital by getting
rid of such regulations as state blue sky laws {regulations
governing securities offerings} which make it harder and more
costly to raise money without offsetting benefits. In
Massachusetts, for example, it can cost as much as $20,000 to
register securities for sale under the blue sky laws.
                                                                                                       

   Q. What are prospects for the future?
   A. The entrepreneurial revolution hasn't run out of steam.
It's alive and well and venture capitalists will continue to
play a role in financing high-potential ventures. Both
investors and entrepreneurs will likely achieve better
financial results in the next five years than they have in
the past five.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
